You can use the Ping Swagger/OpenAPI JSON to generate a **client inside Partner Repository**. Partner Repository will receive the AS400 user snapshot, save/update Postgres, then call Ping using the generated client with these attributes:

```text
givenName
sn
cn
mail
mobile
status
```

## Recommended approach

Do **not** manually write all Ping request/response classes if you already have Swagger JSON. Generate them from the Swagger file.

Flow:

```text
AS400
  -> Partner Repository API
      -> map AS400 request to Partner Repository entities
      -> save/update Postgres
      -> map user entity to Ping request
      -> call Ping API
```

## 1. Put the Swagger file in Partner Repository

Example location:

```text
partner-repository/
└── src/main/resources/openapi/ping-api.json
```

Or:

```text
partner-repository/
└── src/main/openapi/ping-api.json
```

I usually prefer:

```text
src/main/openapi/ping-api.json
```

because it is build-time input, not runtime config.

## 2. Add OpenAPI Generator Maven plugin

In `pom.xml`, add something like this:

```xml
<plugin>
    <groupId>org.openapitools</groupId>
    <artifactId>openapi-generator-maven-plugin</artifactId>
    <version>7.8.0</version>
    <executions>
        <execution>
            <id>generate-ping-client</id>
            <goals>
                <goal>generate</goal>
            </goals>
            <configuration>
                <inputSpec>${project.basedir}/src/main/openapi/ping-api.json</inputSpec>
                <generatorName>java</generatorName>

                <apiPackage>com.bnpp.pf.partner.repository.ping.client.api</apiPackage>
                <modelPackage>com.bnpp.pf.partner.repository.ping.client.model</modelPackage>
                <invokerPackage>com.bnpp.pf.partner.repository.ping.client.invoker</invokerPackage>

                <configOptions>
                    <library>restclient</library>
                    <dateLibrary>java8</dateLibrary>
                    <useJakartaEe>true</useJakartaEe>
                    <openApiNullable>false</openApiNullable>
                </configOptions>
            </configuration>
        </execution>
    </executions>
</plugin>
```

If `restclient` gives issues in your setup, use:

```xml
<library>webclient</library>
```

or:

```xml
<library>resttemplate</library>
```

Since you previously asked about using `RestClient`, `restclient` is the cleaner choice if your Spring Boot version supports it.

## 3. Generate the client

Run:

```bash
mvn clean generate-sources
```

The generated classes will appear under:

```text
target/generated-sources/openapi
```

Make sure IntelliJ marks it as generated source root. Maven usually handles this automatically.

## 4. Create your own wrapper service

Do not call the generated Ping API directly from your AS400 service. Wrap it.

Example:

```java
@Service
public class PingUserClient {

    private final PingUsersApi pingUsersApi;

    public PingUserClient(PingUsersApi pingUsersApi) {
        this.pingUsersApi = pingUsersApi;
    }

    public void createOrUpdateUser(UserEntity user) {
        PingUserRequest request = toPingRequest(user);

        pingUsersApi.createOrUpdateUser(request);
    }

    private PingUserRequest toPingRequest(UserEntity user) {
        PingUserRequest request = new PingUserRequest();

        request.setGivenName(user.getFirstName());
        request.setSn(user.getLastName());
        request.setCn(user.getUsername());
        request.setMail(user.getEmail());
        request.setMobile(user.getPhoneNumber());
        request.setStatus(mapStatus(user.getStatus()));

        return request;
    }

    private String mapStatus(String status) {
        if ("ACTIVE".equalsIgnoreCase(status)) {
            return "active";
        }
        if ("INACTIVE".equalsIgnoreCase(status)) {
            return "inactive";
        }
        return status;
    }
}
```

The exact generated class names may be different depending on the Swagger file. For example, it might generate:

```text
UsersApi
UserApi
CreateUserRequest
UserRepresentation
```

instead of `PingUsersApi` and `PingUserRequest`.

## 5. Map your fields

Based on what you said, the mapping should probably be:

```text
Partner Repository / AS400      Ping
------------------------------------------------
person.firstName                givenName
person.surname                  sn
user.username or userId         cn
person.email                    mail
person.phoneNumber              mobile
person.status                   status
```

Example:

```java
private PingUserRequest toPingRequest(UserSnapshotRequest request, UserEntity user) {
    PingUserRequest pingRequest = new PingUserRequest();

    pingRequest.setGivenName(request.getPerson().getFirstName());
    pingRequest.setSn(request.getPerson().getSurname());
    pingRequest.setCn(user.getUserId());
    pingRequest.setMail(request.getPerson().getEmail());
    pingRequest.setMobile(request.getPerson().getPhoneNumber());
    pingRequest.setStatus(request.getPerson().getStatus());

    return pingRequest;
}
```

For `cn`, confirm with Ping whether they expect:

```text
gps000001
```

or:

```text
John Doe
```

In LDAP-style attributes, `cn` often means “common name”, but in identity integrations it is sometimes used as username/display name. Since your stable user identifier is `gps000001`, I would ask Ping whether `cn` should be the normalized GPS/user id or the full name.

## 6. Configuration in `application.yml`

Add Ping config:

```yaml
ping:
  api:
    base-url: https://ping-api.example.com
    client-id: ${PING_CLIENT_ID}
    client-secret: ${PING_CLIENT_SECRET}
    connect-timeout: 5s
    read-timeout: 10s
```

Then create properties:

```java
@ConfigurationProperties(prefix = "ping.api")
public class PingApiProperties {

    private String baseUrl;
    private String clientId;
    private String clientSecret;
    private Duration connectTimeout;
    private Duration readTimeout;

    // getters and setters
}
```

## 7. Configure the generated client

Depending on the generated library, the config differs slightly. Conceptually:

```java
@Configuration
@EnableConfigurationProperties(PingApiProperties.class)
public class PingClientConfig {

    @Bean
    public ApiClient pingApiClient(PingApiProperties properties) {
        ApiClient apiClient = new ApiClient();
        apiClient.setBasePath(properties.getBaseUrl());

        return apiClient;
    }

    @Bean
    public PingUsersApi pingUsersApi(ApiClient pingApiClient) {
        return new PingUsersApi(pingApiClient);
    }
}
```

If Ping requires OAuth/client credentials, then Partner Repository needs to first get an access token and send:

```http
Authorization: Bearer <token>
```

If they use basic auth, then configure username/password/client credentials in the generated `ApiClient`.

## 8. Where to call Ping in your current flow

Your service should look like this:

```java
@Transactional
public UserSnapshotResponse processSnapshot(UserSnapshotRequest request) {
    UserEntity user = saveOrUpdateUserInPostgres(request);

    pingUserClient.createOrUpdateUser(user);

    return buildAcceptedResponse(user);
}
```

But one important production concern: if Postgres succeeds and Ping fails, you need to decide what happens.

Safer production approach:

```text
1. Save user snapshot in Postgres
2. Save pending Ping sync record
3. Return ACCEPTED
4. Async worker calls Ping
5. Mark Ping sync SUCCESS / FAILED
```

For now, during development, synchronous call is okay. But for production, async/outbox is better.

## 9. What I need from the Swagger file

To give you the exact code, I need to see:

* The endpoint path, for example `/users`, `/scim/v2/Users`, `/identity/users`
* Whether it is `POST`, `PUT`, or `PATCH`
* The request model name
* Authentication method
* Whether `status` is a string, boolean, enum, or nested object

Once you share the Swagger JSON, I can tell you the exact generated API class and exact request object to use.
